      <div xml:id="NA239-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi talaimakaṉ ciṟaippuṟamākac colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said when HE was behind the fence.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA239">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            ñāṉṟa ñāyiṟu kuṭamalai maṟaiya</l>
<l>            māṉṟa mālai makiḻnta paratava</l>
<l>            riṉitupeṟu perumī ṉeḷitaṉiṉ māṟi</l>
<l>            yalava ṉāṭiya pulavumaṇaṉ muṉṟiṟ</l>
<l>            kāmar ciṟukuṭic ceṉṉeṟi vaḻiyi </l>
<l>            ṉāymaṇi potiyaviḻn tāṅku neytaṟ</l>
<l>            pullitaḻ potinta pūnta mitikku</l>
<l>            malla liruṅkaḻi malinīrc cērppaṟ</l>
<l>            kamaintutoḻil kēṭṭaṉṟō vilamē muṉkai</l>
<l>            vārkō lelvaḷai yuṭaiya vāṅki </l>
<l>            muyaṅkeṉak kaliḻnta vivvū</l>
<l>            reṟṟā vatukolyāṉ maṟṟoṉṟu ceyiṉē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>As for listening<note place="foot">For the type of negation where the perfective neuter singular in -<term xml:lang="ta">aṉṟu</term> has to be analysed as an verbal noun see note on NA 27, for the marking with -<term xml:lang="ta">ō</term> see note on NA 175.6.</note> to the request(?)<note place="foot">Do we have to understand <term xml:lang="ta">toḻil</term> in the sense of <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟai</term> here?</note>, consenting</l>
<l rend="indent">to the man from the coast of abundant waters,</l>
<l rend="indent">with plentiful dark backwaters,</l>
<l rend="indent">where, when the descending sun vanishes behind the western mountain,</l>
<l rend="indent2">the fishermen, delighted<note place="foot">T.V.G. explains the delight of the fishermen by the consummation of toddy; this is another meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">makiḻ</term>.</note> in gloomy evening,</l>
<l rend="indent3">since they had exchanged easily a big fish pleasantly obtained,<note place="foot">T.V.G. reads here, quite tendentiously, that the drunken fishermen sell their big fish for too low a price, but the text does not seem to suggest anything of the kind, apart from that they seem to have been lucky in catching a big fish (which would explain their delight quite innocently).</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">on [their] way on the path to the desirable small hamlet</l>
<l rend="indent2">with front yards to the fish-reeking sand where crabs were playing,</l>
<l rend="indent">trample the flowers themselves<note place="foot">The better attested variant reads <term xml:lang="ta">pūm tapa mitikkum</term>: "they trample so that the flowers get destroyed".</note>, that bundled [their] low(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pul itaḻ</term> is explained by T.V.G. as outer petals.</note> petals,</l>
<l rend="indent2">of the waterlilies blue as an opened hoard of choice sapphires,</l>
<l rend="indent4">  we didn’t.</l>
<l>What will become</l>
<l rend="indent2">of this village that has started weeping “embrace [him]</l>
<l rend="indent">bending the bright bangles in long row on [your] forearm up to breaking,”</l>
<l rend="indent4">if I do just the one thing?</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
